Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, totaling 29 percent
A significant weakening of both parties of the so far great coalition and a clear strengthening of the right-wing populist parties, following the first preliminary results, brought the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly severe losses, where the position of former chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the tip.
On the other hand, the election leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Carinthian head of state Jörg Haider, prepares for a triumphal return to federal politics.
According to the previous results, S & D (SPÖ) remains strongest in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but loses 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse, the ÖVP lost nearly nine percent of the votes at 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in the Austrian post-war history, and this is a really disastrous result, especially for the People's Party, which called for the early elections.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had resigned from the coalition, the People's Party had a clear advantage over the SPÖ.
However, the voters probably punished the party for failing the government.
Already in the first reactions to the results there were speculations about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice-cancer Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could already be the case on Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party board.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the great coalition from SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both the right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) received 18 percent for the time being, the BZÖ 11 percent for the time being - the Social Democrats expressed their fears that the year 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had agreed with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it separated from the BZÖ) with regard to a common government, which had even caused sanctions from the European Union.
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with each party, clearly relies on this development and goes on a return to Vienna to Austrian federal politics.
In addition, the Green Party moved into the Parliament, which suffered slight losses and slipped from the third to the fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four-percent burden and therefore did not go to Parliament.
