Turkey expands the diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey sought to join the European Union, the European powers were interested in penetrated deep into the hinterland of Turkey.
On the eastern side of the Bosporus, perhaps just 20 steps within Asia, stands one of the finest relics of this failed, imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by the two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in Neo-Renaissance style.
That's at least what the guides tell you.
The building sits riding at the end of the platform with a tower at every corner of the front and thus looks like some provincial German town hall.
The rock is dirty.
The whole building is falling apart, for example.
But once you're inside the vaulted ticket desk, there's no doubt about the grandeur of the project, its western most accessible.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, Anatolia-Baghdad Society.
Germany, which was a funnel in the imperialist game, had to implement its ambitions to dominate the Middle East, by means of a train link to Damascus, Baghdad, and further beyond what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperialist schemes paralysed during the first world war.
His railway tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and its Arabs.
The relative isolation from its surrounding region, created by the insurmountable limits of the cold war, has disappeared.
British forces came out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies from Palestine and Syria
And there was also bad news for the Hyderpasha station.
In 1917, a munitions train flew into the air, destroying the artistic roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly disintegrated, largely passing from history.
Nowadays, however, this railway line serves, at least symbolically, as a gateway to Anatolia and all east of it to highlight the expansion of the diplomatic horizon of Turkey.
The ruling judicial and development party, the ACP, has introduced a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the neighbouring regions, generated by the borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there is a policy of approach.
Remarkably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian splitter groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iran and Iraq and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to assess the key elements of this new foreign policy, I have boarded the night train to Ankara, Turkey's capital, to visit one of the ACP's leading foreign policy experts, Mr Suat Kinikioglu.
The next morning, about ten and a half hours later, after a bumpy ride on tracks that produced the same step of the old world in the well-known documentation "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, which is considered a new city, for the new secular state project to turn my back on the Ottoman past.
However, the ACP, known for its Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in Turkish unity
This has caused some mistrust in the West, especially in Washington.
A taxi took me to the main office of the AKP, a specially made, state-of-the-art stone and steel construction, in a developing suburb surrounded by semi-finished shopping centers and pubs where middle managers met in suits, both men and women, to complete the first business of the day.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a middle-right politician of almost any other political party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he even packed a blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is now to reintegrate Turkey with its immediate neighbours.
The Cold War was an exception," he tells me.
Turkey had been cut off from its hinterland.
Nowadays, it has to look east and west at the same time.
There wouldn't be either one or the other.
She'd have to do both.
"But surely Turkey could at some point," I asked, "be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "didn't have to make this decision."
He then raised a point that almost everyone I was talking to almost routinely said: Turkey's relations, not only to the Middle East but also to the Caucasus and around the Black Sea, are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, can, in the transferred sense, drive Europe as a whole on straight rails east towards Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha's train station, after another largely sleepless night, I thought of these two German rulers, Mr. Ritter and Mr. Conu, who had watched the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East could now, to a large extent, be in the hands of Turkey.
And when I was waiting for the ferry that was to take me back over the Bosporus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At that time, at least there seemed to be little doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating country.
