In order to advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, more precisely, by bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight goes back to the swarming behaviour of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C and represents the first step in accident prevention technologies.
The engineers from the technical development centre of Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, Head of Technology-PR and R&D-Brand Management, the BR23C is an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety sign.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds its own oval air space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facet eyes of the bee, which can see over a 300 degree angle in all directions, which allows them to fly in their personal airspace without interruption.
To replicate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
It notices obstacles in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and in the radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to a board's microprocessor, which is directly translated into a signal for avoiding collision
`In the moment that obstacle is noticed, the little robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels around 90o or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference with other systems is that this elusive maneuver is absolutely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot could not be able to react with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles,' explains Toshyuki Andoh, the director of the mobility laboratory and the executive engineer of this project.
In contrast to a bee, the robot can not deviate up or down, but also not overeck; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways as the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and deceleration functions so that the small robot avoids collisions.
This device only needs to process the information for a few seconds and act on the basis of this information.
It does not require either the information or intuitive logic of the maneuvers done, so it can work continuously with only a few dozen KB of the storage space.
That sounds surprising, but it's not about the GBs and not even about the MBs of the storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts over the next ten years with the serial cars.
The robot works with lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and longer than the diversity of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite, in order to lead to the goal while driving and to avoid the obstacles on the road.
