Morgan Stanley announced the entry of Mitsubishi UFJ Financial Group (MUFG) into its company, which would be the first bank in Japan to spend $9 billion and thus take over 21% of its capital, a innovation due to a strong fall in its stock exchange price.
A week after a preliminary agreement was made public, the two banks declared that MUFG will buy 9.9% of Morgan Stanley's common share at a uniform price of $25.25, resulting in a total of three billion dollars.
The assumed price is below 19% of the stock's price of 31 August.
MUFG will invest an additional six billion dollars in the acquisition of convertible shares, which will secure a profit of 10% and can be resold at a price of 31.25 dollars.
Morgan Stanley stated that the global business will be carried out on the basis of a single average price of 29 dollars, i.e. 28 % above the current price value.
However, the Morgan Stanley share decreased by 6.79% to 23.07 dollars at 17.00 GMT.
"This strategic link represents an important opportunity to accelerate the transition from Morgan Stanley to the status of a holding bank," said John Mack, Director General of the American Group.
Morgan Stanley took on this status last week, which should enable him to expand their business to new areas, but under the supervision of the Federal Reserve.
Their connection with MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis forces the biggest names of Wall Street to take a much more cautious attitude than before.
The arrangements presented on Monday also show that the agreement has changed over the last few days: Last Monday Morgan had simply declared that it would sell up to 20% of its shares to Japan for about 8.5 billion dollars.
"A week ago," said Toshhide Mizuno, CEO of MUFG, in Tokyo, "we thought that the stake would consist entirely of common shares.
But in view of the current economic and market situation, we wanted to reduce the risks and secure ourselves.'
Based on a balanced average price, MUFG will pay 7% below its price for its Morgan Stanley shares.
And the business will start with a reduction in profits by about 20% per share.
The agreement provides that in one year, MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential shares into common shares if the latter are exchanged more than 50% above the sales value within a given period, i.e. approximately 47 dollars.
Morgan Stanley assures that the funds supplied by MUFG will allow him to use investment opportunities, to strengthen their balance sheet and to increase their sales.
However, a Group press spokesperson refused to provide more detailed information on the strategic projects of the two new allies.
After the investment of MUFG, Morgan Stanley should be able to record a debt ratio of about 15%, one of the best in this sector.
Morgan explained that he had 'clearly' reduced his balance since the end of August.
